04576nam a22006135i 9780226817767DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20222022ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780226817767  a(DE-B1597)618903  a(OCoLC)1322123882  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aP37.5.S68 7aART0000002bisacsh04a302.2/2422231 aWilke, Tobias, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSound Writing :bExperimental Modernism and the Poetics of Articulation /cTobias Wilke. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (368 p.) :b5 color plates, 39 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- t1. Voice Figures: Visible Sound and the Poetics of Articulation (1787–1965) -- t2. Toward a Science of Verse: Speech Movements, Graphic Inscription, and the Study of Poetry (1871–1915) -- t3. Mama—Papa— Dada: Poetic Expression at the Threshold of Language (1916–1947) -- t4. Verbi-Voco- Visual Explorations: Experimental Modernism in a Technical Age (1947–1967) -- tAcknowledgments -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aConsiders the avant-garde rethinking of poetic language in terms of physical speech production. Avant-garde writers and artists of the twentieth century radically reconceived poetic language, appropriating scientific theories and techniques as they turned their attention to the physical process of spoken language. This modernist “sound writing” focused on the bodily production of speech, which it rendered in poetic, legible, graphic form. Modernist sound writing aims to capture the acoustic phenomenon of vocal articulation by graphic means. Tobias Wilke considers sound writing from its inception in nineteenth-century disciplines like physiology and experimental phonetics, following its role in the aesthetic practices of the interwar avant-garde and through to its reemergence in the postwar period. These projects work with the possibility of crossing over from the audible to the visible, from speech to notation, from body to trace. Employing various techniques and concepts, this search for new possibilities played a central role in the transformation of poetry into a site of radical linguistic experimentation. Considering the works of writers and artists—including Raoul Hausmann, Kurt Schwitters, Viktor Shklovsky, Hugo Ball, Charles Olson, and Marshall McLuhan—Wilke offers a fresh look at the history of the twentieth-century avant-garde.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aElocution. 0aSound poetry. 0aSound. 0aSpeech. 7aART / General.2bisacsh  aavant-garde, sound, poetry, articulation, history of science.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Architecture and Design 2022z9783110992793oZDB-23-DAD08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Arts, Architecture and Design 2022 Englishz978311099281608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishz978311099389908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022z9783110994810oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076650940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226817767423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226817767/original  a978-3-11-076650-9  University of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  a978-3-11-099281-6  EBOOK PACKAGE Arts, Architecture and Design 2022 Englishb2022  a978-3-11-099389-9  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishb2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-DADb2022  aZDB-23-DGGb2022